<author><name><![CDATA[zcorpan]]></name></author>
<updated>2007-02-22T19:32:26+00:00</updated>
<id>https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=5&amp;p=21#p21</id>
<link href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=5&amp;p=21#p21"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Should &lt;address&gt; be more general-purpose?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=5&amp;p=21#p21"><![CDATA[
<blockquote><div><cite>sfraser wrote:</cite><br />I've never used &lt;address&gt;: it is an inline element in HTML 4.01;<br /></div></blockquote>No, it's a block-level element in HTML4. (The content model is inline, but that's not the same thing.)<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>sfraser wrote:</cite><br />HTML5 allows &lt;address&gt; to be block-level or strictly-inline (though the current specification does not show an example for block-level).<br /></div></blockquote>No, <a href="http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/#the-address" class="postlink">&lt;address&gt; in HTML5</a> is a block-level element. The content model is inline-level content.<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>sfraser wrote:</cite><br />Block-Level<br /><br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: </dt><dd><code>&lt;address&gt;<br />&lt;ul&gt;<br />&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;../People/Raggett/&quot;&gt;Dave Raggett&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; <br />&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;../People/Arnaud/&quot;&gt;Arnaud Le Hors&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;<br />&lt;li&gt;contact persons for the &lt;a href=&quot;Activity&quot;&gt;W3C HTML Activity&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;<br />&lt;li&gt;$Date: 1999/12/24 23:37:50 $&lt;/li&gt;<br />&lt;/ul&gt;<br />&lt;/address&gt;<br /></code></dd></dl><br /></div></blockquote>Here, the &lt;address&gt; is a block-level element (it always is), and it contains inline-level content. The &lt;ul&gt; above (which can be either block-level or structured inline) is structured inline (because &lt;address&gt; only allows inline children).<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>sfraser wrote:</cite><br />Strictly-Inline<br /><br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: </dt><dd><code>&lt;address&gt;<br />&lt;a href=&quot;../People/Raggett/&quot;&gt;Dave Raggett&lt;/a&gt;, <br />&lt;a href=&quot;../People/Arnaud/&quot;&gt;Arnaud Le Hors&lt;/a&gt;,<br />contact persons for the &lt;a href=&quot;Activity&quot;&gt;W3C HTML Activity&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;<br />$Date: 1999/12/24 23:37:50 $<br />&lt;/address&gt;<br /></code></dd></dl><br /></div></blockquote>Again, the &lt;address&gt; is block and its contents are inline. The &lt;a&gt; and &lt;br&gt; elements are strictly inline elements, so they are allowed where inline-level content is allowed (like in &lt;address&gt;).<br /><br />Note also that &quot;$Date: 1999/12/24 23:37:50 $&quot; is not contact information and so is not appropriate to use in &lt;address&gt; (as currently defined).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4">zcorpan</a> — Thu Feb 22, 2007 7:32 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
